WEBVTT

﻿1
00:00:12.507 --> 00:00:13.662
Visible from space,
从太空看，

2
00:00:13.686 --> 00:00:15.313
the Okavango Delta
奥卡万戈三角洲，

3
00:00:15.337 --> 00:00:20.051
is Africa's largest remaining intact wetland wilderness.
是非洲剩余最大、 最完整的野生湿地荒野。

4
00:00:20.075 --> 00:00:25.916
This shining delta in landlocked Botswana is the jewel of the Kalahari,
这个位于博茨瓦纳内陆的三角洲， 是卡拉哈里闪闪发亮的宝石，

5
00:00:25.940 --> 00:00:30.369
more valuable than diamonds to the world's largest diamond producer
比世界上最大的 钻石生产商的更有价值，

6
00:00:30.393 --> 00:00:32.782
and celebrated in 2014
并于 2014 年，

7
00:00:32.806 --> 00:00:36.291
as our planet's 1000th UNESCO World Heritage Site.
被列入为地球上第 1000 处 联合国教科文组织世界遗产。

8
00:00:36.315 --> 00:00:39.220
Now, what you see here are the two major tributaries,
现在，你可以看到的 是两条主要支流，

9
00:00:39.244 --> 00:00:41.261
the Cuito and the Cubango,
奎托和奥卡万戈河，

10
00:00:41.285 --> 00:00:45.411
disappearing up north into the little-known Angolan highlands.
向北逐渐消失在 鲜为人知的安哥拉高地。

11
00:00:45.435 --> 00:00:49.734
This is the largest undeveloped river basin on the planet,
这个是我们地球上 最大的未开发的流域，

12
00:00:49.758 --> 00:00:51.881
spanning an area larger than California.
是比加利福尼亚州 面积更大的区域。

13
00:00:52.910 --> 00:00:56.990
These vast, undeveloped Angolan watersheds were frozen in time
这片巨大的安哥拉流域 之所以未被开发，

14
00:00:57.014 --> 00:00:59.372
by 27 years of civil war.
与 27 年的内战有关。

15
00:00:59.396 --> 00:01:03.397
In fact, Africa's largest tank battle since World War II
事实上，非洲自第二次世界 大战以来最大的坦克战，

16
00:01:03.421 --> 00:01:06.853
was fought over a bridge crossing the Okavango's Cuito River.
就发生在穿越奥卡万戈三角洲 内奎托河上的一座桥上。

17
00:01:06.877 --> 00:01:08.268
There on the right,
就在这右边，

18
00:01:08.292 --> 00:01:10.046
disappearing off into the unknown,
消失在未知之中，

19
00:01:10.070 --> 00:01:12.419
into the "Terra do fim do mundo" --
消失在“地球尽头（葡萄牙语）”，

20
00:01:12.443 --> 00:01:14.371
the land at the end of the earth,
地球尽头。

21
00:01:14.395 --> 00:01:17.284
as it was known by the first Portuguese explorers.
正如第一批葡萄牙 探险家所了解的那样。

22
00:01:18.095 --> 00:01:21.468
In 2001, at the age of 22,
2001年，当时我22岁，

23
00:01:21.492 --> 00:01:25.384
I took a job as head of housekeeping at Vundumtiki Camp
我获得了一份在Vundumtiki 营地看家的工作，

24
00:01:25.408 --> 00:01:27.508
in the Okavango Delta ...
位置就在奥卡万戈三角洲，

25
00:01:27.532 --> 00:01:32.136
a patchwork mosaic of channels, floodplains, lagoons
那里汇集了海峡，涝原和泻湖，

26
00:01:32.160 --> 00:01:35.428
and thousands upon thousands of islands to explore.
以及等待探索的成千岛屿。

27
00:01:36.109 --> 00:01:39.769
Home to the largest remaining population of elephants on the planet.
这里是地球上仅存最大的 大象野生家园。

28
00:01:40.131 --> 00:01:45.049
Rhinos are airlifted in C130s to find sanctuary in this wilderness.
犀牛通过军机C130s空运， 也来到在这片荒野中寻找庇护所。

29
00:01:45.885 --> 00:01:47.035
Lion,
还有狮子，

30
00:01:47.059 --> 00:01:48.301
leopard,
豹子，

31
00:01:48.325 --> 00:01:49.553
hyena,
鬣狗，

32
00:01:49.577 --> 00:01:50.748
wild dog,
野狗，

33
00:01:50.772 --> 00:01:52.045
cheetah,
猎豹，

34
00:01:52.069 --> 00:01:55.844
ancient baobab trees that stand like cathedrals
以及像大教堂一样伫立的 古老面包树，

35
00:01:55.868 --> 00:01:57.355
under the Milky Way.
他们都存在于这片银河之下。

36
00:01:57.379 --> 00:02:00.946
Here, I discovered something obvious:
在这里，我发现

37
00:02:00.970 --> 00:02:04.068
wilderness is our natural habitat, too.
荒野也是我们人类的自然栖息地。

38
00:02:04.092 --> 00:02:07.972
We need these last wild places to reconnect with who we really are.
我们需要这片最后的荒野 来重新思考我们真实的存在。

39
00:02:09.949 --> 00:02:11.100
We --
我们 ——

40
00:02:11.124 --> 00:02:12.422
all seven billion of us --
我们所有的70亿人——

41
00:02:12.446 --> 00:02:15.877
must never forget we are a biological species
绝不能忘记， 我们也是一种生物，

42
00:02:15.901 --> 00:02:18.950
forever bound to this particular biological world.
我们与这个生物世界， 永远存在着联系。

43
00:02:18.974 --> 00:02:21.241
Like the waves connected to the ocean,
就像浪花离不开大海，

44
00:02:21.265 --> 00:02:22.822
we cannot exist apart from it --
我们也无法与 这个生物世界分离——

45
00:02:22.846 --> 00:02:27.634
a constant flow of atoms and energy between individuals and species
个体和物种之间不断的 原子和能量流动，

46
00:02:27.658 --> 00:02:29.305
around the world in a day
每天都在这个世界的各个角落，

47
00:02:29.329 --> 00:02:31.421
and out into the cosmos.
和宇宙之外发生着。

48
00:02:32.842 --> 00:02:36.454
Our fates are forever connected to the millions of species
我们的命运永远与 数以百万计的物种联系在一起，

49
00:02:36.478 --> 00:02:40.589
we rely on directly and indirectly every day.
通过直接或间接的方式，彼此依赖。

50
00:02:42.057 --> 00:02:43.327
Four years ago,
四年以前，

51
00:02:43.351 --> 00:02:47.690
it was declared that 50 percent of all wildlife around the world
有消息宣称，在过去的40年间，

52
00:02:47.714 --> 00:02:50.055
had disappeared in just 40 years.
全球有50%的野生动物消失了。

53
00:02:51.320 --> 00:02:54.356
This is a mass drowning of 15,000 wildebeests
两年前，我在马赛马拉，

54
00:02:54.380 --> 00:02:57.742
that I witnessed in the Maasai Mara two years ago.
亲眼目睹了15000头角马的溺亡。

55
00:02:57.766 --> 00:03:00.099
This is definitely our fault.
这绝对是我们人类的过错。

56
00:03:01.196 --> 00:03:05.403
By 2020, global wildlife populations are projected to have fallen
据预测，全球野生动物 总数到了2020年

57
00:03:05.427 --> 00:03:07.617
by a staggering two-thirds.
会再度减少三分之二。

58
00:03:07.641 --> 00:03:09.832
We are the sixth extinction
我们正位于第六次大灭绝中，

59
00:03:09.856 --> 00:03:12.971
because we left no safe space for millions of species
我们没有为数百万 物种留下安全空间

60
00:03:12.995 --> 00:03:15.078
to sustainably coexist.
来和我们一起和谐共存。

61
00:03:15.994 --> 00:03:21.797
Now, since 2010, I have poled myself eight times across the Okavango Delta
自2010年以来，我撑船 横跨了八次奥卡万戈三角洲，

62
00:03:21.821 --> 00:03:24.560
to conduct detailed scientific surveys
沿着200英里的河流，

63
00:03:24.584 --> 00:03:27.954
along a 200-mile, 18-day research transect.
展开为期18天的科学调研。

64
00:03:27.978 --> 00:03:29.183
Now, why am I doing this?
为什么我要这样做呢？

65
00:03:28.873 --> 00:03:30.524
Why am I risking my life each year?
为什么每年都冒着 这样的生命危险呢？

66
00:03:30.898 --> 00:03:33.119
I'm doing this because we need this information
因为我们需要这些信息，

67
00:03:32.829 --> 00:03:35.063
to benchmark this near-pristine wilderness
需要在对上游的开发启动之前，

68
00:03:35.167 --> 00:03:37.129
before upstream development happens.
去记录这些原始荒野的生态标准。

69
00:03:37.672 --> 00:03:42.704
These are the Wayeyi river bushmen, the people of the Okavango Delta.
这些是Wayeyi河丛林人， 奥卡万戈三角洲的原住民。

70
00:03:43.143 --> 00:03:45.963
They have taught me all I know about the Mother Okavango --
他们教给我有关母亲 奥卡万戈的一切——

71
00:03:45.987 --> 00:03:47.653
about presence in the wild.
一切有关野外的存在。

72
00:03:47.677 --> 00:03:51.689
Our shared pilgrimage across the Okavango Delta each year
我们每年都乘着独木舟， 共同踏上向着奥卡万戈三角洲的

73
00:03:51.713 --> 00:03:53.690
in our mokoros or dugout canoes --
朝圣之旅，

74
00:03:53.714 --> 00:03:56.589
remembers millenia living in the wild.
一起铭记像在千年以前 野外生存的情景。

75
00:03:57.625 --> 00:03:59.392
Ten thousand years ago,
一万年前，

76
00:03:59.416 --> 00:04:02.212
our entire world was wilderness.
我们的整个世界都是荒野。

77
00:04:02.810 --> 00:04:08.690
Today, wilderness is all that remains of that world, now gone.
今天，荒野成了那个世界的遗迹， 现在也在消失了。

78
00:04:09.495 --> 00:04:13.011
Ten thousand years ago, we were as we are today:
一万年前，我们和今天一样：

79
00:04:13.035 --> 00:04:16.850
a modern, dreaming intelligence unlike anything seen before.
向往着未知的未来。

80
00:04:16.874 --> 00:04:19.323
Living in the wilderness is what taught us to speak,
野外生存教会我们说话，

81
00:04:19.347 --> 00:04:22.929
to seek technologies like fire and stone, bow and arrow,
教会我们寻找像火和石头，弓和箭，

82
00:04:22.953 --> 00:04:24.785
medicine and poison,
药和毒药，

83
00:04:24.809 --> 00:04:26.978
to domesticate plants and animals
教会我们驯化植物和动物，

84
00:04:27.002 --> 00:04:30.257
and rely on each other and all living things around us.
教会我们彼此依赖，共同依存。

85
00:04:30.281 --> 00:04:32.656
We are these last wildernesses --
我们是最后的荒野——

86
00:04:32.680 --> 00:04:34.008
every one of us.
每个人都是。

87
00:04:34.621 --> 00:04:36.688
Over 80 percent of our planet's land surface
我们地球上超过80%的土地表面，

88
00:04:36.712 --> 00:04:39.861
is now experiencing measurable human impact:
在经历着可衡量的人类影响：

89
00:04:39.885 --> 00:04:41.234
habitat destruction
栖息地毁灭，

90
00:04:41.258 --> 00:04:45.102
and illegal wildlife trade are decimating global wildlife populations.
同时非法野生动物贸易 正摧毁着全球野生动物种群。

91
00:04:45.126 --> 00:04:49.062
We urgently need to create safe space for these wild animals.
我们迫切需要为这些 野生动物创造安全的空间。

92
00:04:49.586 --> 00:04:51.331
So in late 2014,
所以在2014年底，

93
00:04:51.355 --> 00:04:53.936
we launched an ambitious project to do just that:
我们为了这个目的 推出了这个雄心勃勃的项目：

94
00:04:53.960 --> 00:04:55.697
explore and protect.
探索和保护野外生存地。

95
00:04:56.292 --> 00:04:58.217
By mid-May 2015,
到2015年年中，

96
00:04:58.241 --> 00:05:00.570
we had pioneered access through active minefields
我们从活跃的地区开始，

97
00:05:00.594 --> 00:05:03.237
to the undocumented source lake of the Cuito River --
已经到达了奎托河 从未记载的源头湖——

98
00:05:03.261 --> 00:05:05.361
this otherworldly place;
这个世外桃源，

99
00:05:05.385 --> 00:05:07.345
an ancient, untouched wilderness.
一片古老而又未经破坏的土地。

100
00:05:08.205 --> 00:05:09.500
By the 21st of May,
到5月21日为止，

101
00:05:09.524 --> 00:05:12.833
we had launched the Okavango megatransect ...
我们进行了一次 对奥卡万戈的大型探索，

102
00:05:12.857 --> 00:05:14.518
in seven dugout canoes;
派出了七艘独木舟；

103
00:05:14.542 --> 00:05:18.619
1,500 miles, 121 days later,
全程1500英里，历时121天，

104
00:05:18.643 --> 00:05:21.153
all of the poling, paddling and intensive research
在划桨和调研等紧凑的活动下，

105
00:05:21.177 --> 00:05:24.939
got us across the entire river basin to Lake Xau in the Kalahari Desert,
我们跨过了成片河流流域， 到达喀拉哈里沙漠里的湖泊，

106
00:05:24.963 --> 00:05:28.267
480 kilometers past the Okavango Delta.
在距离奥卡万戈三角洲 480公里的地方。

107
00:05:28.900 --> 00:05:31.464
My entire world became the water:
我的世界全是水， 和与水相关的一切：

108
00:05:31.488 --> 00:05:35.249
every ripple, eddy, lily pad and current ...
每一道波纹，涡流， 潮水，每一片莲叶，

109
00:05:36.217 --> 00:05:37.966
any sign of danger,
每一道危险的提示，

110
00:05:37.990 --> 00:05:39.864
every sign of life.
以及每一道生命的迹象。

111
00:05:40.772 --> 00:05:43.724
Now imagine millions of sweat bees choking the air around you,
想象一下，数以百万计的蜜蜂， 围绕着你，抽空你周围的空气，

112
00:05:43.748 --> 00:05:44.985
flesh-eating bacteria,
肉食性细菌，

113
00:05:45.009 --> 00:05:48.399
the constant threat of a landmine going off
随时可能踩中的地雷，

114
00:05:48.423 --> 00:05:50.755
or an unseen hippo capsizing your mokoro.
以及隐藏在水中准备 弄翻独木舟的河马。

115
00:05:50.779 --> 00:05:53.693
These are the scenes moments after a hippo did just that --
这些是我们在 被河马袭击后的几个场景，

116
00:05:53.717 --> 00:05:55.997
thrusting its tusks through the hull of my boat.
我们的船壳被它的长牙穿透，

117
00:05:56.021 --> 00:05:57.706
You can see the two holes --
你看，就是这两个洞——

118
00:05:57.730 --> 00:05:59.812
puncture wounds in the base of the hull --
刺穿船壳底座——

119
00:05:59.836 --> 00:06:01.560
absolutely terrifying
真的是非常可怕，

120
00:06:01.584 --> 00:06:03.730
and completely my fault.
而且都是我的过错。

121
00:06:03.754 --> 00:06:05.117
(Laughter)
（笑）

122
00:06:05.141 --> 00:06:07.224
Many, many portages,
有非常非常多次，

123
00:06:07.248 --> 00:06:10.950
tree blockages and capsizes in rocky rapids.
船只被树木阻挡了， 或者撞击到石头发生了侧翻。

124
00:06:12.724 --> 00:06:14.845
You're living on rice and beans,
想象一下，生活在水稻与大豆间，

125
00:06:14.869 --> 00:06:16.779
bathing in a bucket of cold water
在冷水桶中洗澡，

126
00:06:16.803 --> 00:06:19.634
and paddling a marathon six to eight hours every single day.
每天还要进行 6到8小时的划桨马拉松。

127
00:06:19.658 --> 00:06:21.626
After 121 days of this,
121天之后，

128
00:06:21.650 --> 00:06:23.977
I'd forgotten the PIN numbers to my bank accounts
我完全忘记了自己银行卡的密码，

129
00:06:24.001 --> 00:06:25.451
and logins for social media --
也不记得怎样登陆 我的社交账号——

130
00:06:25.475 --> 00:06:27.505
a complete systems reboot.
我的大脑系统仿佛重启了一般。

131
00:06:27.861 --> 00:06:30.374
You ask me now if I miss it,
如果你问我是否想念那趟旅行，

132
00:06:30.398 --> 00:06:32.691
and I will tell you I am still there.
我会告诉你，我依然在那里。

133
00:06:33.609 --> 00:06:36.130
Now why do we need to save places we hardly ever go?
你可能会问，为什么我们要去拯救 一个我们也许永远不会去的地方？

134
00:06:36.473 --> 00:06:38.222
Why do we need to save places
我们为什么要去拯救那些

135
00:06:38.246 --> 00:06:40.345
where you have to risk your life to be there?
需要我们冒着生命危险 才能到达的地方？

136
00:06:40.369 --> 00:06:44.613
Now, I'm not a religious or particularly spiritual person,
我不是一个有宗教信仰的人，

137
00:06:44.637 --> 00:06:45.807
but in the wild,
但在野外，

138
00:06:45.831 --> 00:06:49.483
I believe I've experienced the birthplace of religion.
我确信我来到了信仰诞生的地方。

139
00:06:50.156 --> 00:06:53.244
Standing in front of an elephant far away from anywhere
身处荒蛮之地，站在大象的面前，

140
00:06:53.268 --> 00:06:56.284
is the closest I will ever get to God.
我仿佛来到了离上帝最近的地方。

141
00:06:57.078 --> 00:06:59.423
Moses, Buddha, Muhammad, Jesus,
摩西，浮屠，穆罕默德，耶稣，

142
00:06:59.447 --> 00:07:01.731
the Hindu teachers, prophets and mystics,
印度教教师，先知，神秘主义者，

143
00:07:01.755 --> 00:07:03.263
all went into the wilderness --
他们都去过野外——

144
00:07:03.287 --> 00:07:05.160
up into the mountains, into the desert,
高上山岗，深入沙漠，

145
00:07:04.840 --> 00:07:07.434
to sit quietly and listen for those secrets
静静地坐在那里， 就能聆听所有的秘密，

146
00:07:07.438 --> 00:07:09.951
that were to guide their societies for millennia.
指引我们社会发展千年的奥秘。

147
00:07:09.975 --> 00:07:12.485
I go into the Okavango on my mokoro.
我撑着独木舟来到奥卡万戈。

148
00:07:13.024 --> 00:07:14.644
You must join me one day.
在未来的某一天，加入我吧。

149
00:07:16.342 --> 00:07:19.332
Over 50 percent of the remaining wilderness is unprotected.
仅存的荒野中，超过一半未经保护。

150
00:07:19.756 --> 00:07:21.668
A huge opportunity --
这是一个非常大的机遇，

151
00:07:21.692 --> 00:07:23.303
a chance for us all.
对于所有人而言都是一个机遇。

152
00:07:25.073 --> 00:07:27.498
We need to act with great urgency.
我们需要立刻采取行动。

153
00:07:27.522 --> 00:07:29.907
Since the 2015 megatransect,
因为自从2015年大调查以来，

154
00:07:29.931 --> 00:07:32.989
we have explored all major rivers of the Okavango River basin,
我们探索了奥卡万戈流域中 所有的主要河流，

155
00:07:33.013 --> 00:07:36.946
covering a life-changing 4,000 miles of detailed research transects
覆盖超过4000英里的详尽调研。

156
00:07:36.970 --> 00:07:38.260
on our dugout canoes
就靠着我们的独木舟，

157
00:07:38.284 --> 00:07:40.301
and our fat-tire mountain bikes.
和我们的山地自行车。

158
00:07:40.325 --> 00:07:42.797
We now have 57 top scientists
我们现在有57名顶尖科学家，

159
00:07:42.821 --> 00:07:46.798
rediscovering what we call the Okavango-Zambezi water tower --
重新探索我们所说的 Okavango-Zambezi水源，

160
00:07:46.822 --> 00:07:53.467
this vast, post-war wilderness with undocumented source lakes,
这片广阔的战后荒野， 有未经记载的河流源头湖泊，

161
00:07:53.491 --> 00:07:58.006
unnamed waterfalls in what is Africa's largest remaining Miombo woodland.
有非洲最大Miombo林地的未名瀑布。

162
00:07:59.300 --> 00:08:02.062
We've now discovered 24 new species to science
我们发现了24种新物种，

163
00:08:02.086 --> 00:08:04.352
and hundreds of species not known to be there.
和数百种迁徙到那里的物种。

164
00:08:04.944 --> 00:08:08.166
This year, we start the process, with the Angolan government,
今年，我们开始和安哥拉政府合作，

165
00:08:08.190 --> 00:08:11.990
to establish one of the largest systems of protected areas in the world
建立世界上最大的保护区系统之一，

166
00:08:12.014 --> 00:08:14.416
to preserve the Okavango-Zambezi water tower
用以保护我们探索到的，

167
00:08:14.440 --> 00:08:15.615
we have been exploring.
那个Okavango-Zambezi水源。

168
00:08:15.639 --> 00:08:19.586
Downstream, this represents water security for millions of people
下游，有着数百万 依靠这口水源生存的人民，

169
00:08:19.610 --> 00:08:22.927
and more than half of the elephants remaining on this planet.
以及地球上超过一半的 大象所栖息的地方。

170
00:08:22.951 --> 00:08:27.058
There is no doubt this is the biggest conservation opportunity in Africa
毫无疑问，这是数十年来非洲

171
00:08:27.082 --> 00:08:28.328
in decades.
最大的环保机遇。

172
00:08:28.352 --> 00:08:29.762
Over the next 10 to 15 years,
在接下来的10到15年间，

173
00:08:29.786 --> 00:08:32.059
we need to make an unprecedented investment
我们需要史无前例地关注和投资，

174
00:08:32.083 --> 00:08:34.589
in the preservation of wilderness around the world.
来保护世界各地的荒野。

175
00:08:35.168 --> 00:08:36.318
To me,
对于我个人而言，

176
00:08:36.342 --> 00:08:41.001
preserving wilderness is far more than simply protecting ecosystems
保护荒野远远不止 简单地保护生态系统，

177
00:08:41.025 --> 00:08:44.016
that clean the water we drink and create the air we breathe.
不止是保护饮用水或者保护空气。

178
00:08:44.502 --> 00:08:48.782
Preserving wilderness protects our basic human right to be wild --
保护荒野，也就是保护我们 去体验狂野的基本人权——

179
00:08:48.806 --> 00:08:51.463
our basic human rights to explore.
保护我们探索的基本人权。

180
00:08:52.061 --> 00:08:53.291
Thank you.
谢谢大家。

181
00:08:53.315 --> 00:08:59.978
(Applause)
（掌声）